  <h2>Rothamsted's Classical Experiments</h2>
  <p>Soon after John Lawes started his collaboration with Henry Gilbert, they 
    began a series of field experiments to examine the effects of inorganic fertilisers 
    and organic manures on the nutrition and yield of a number of important crops. 
    Seven of the experiments that were started in the middle of the 19<sup>th</sup> 
    century are still going today. Most of them have undergone changes to maintain 
    their scientific and agricultural relevance but they retain many of the original 
    treatments and have an unbroken history that extends over more than 150 years. 
    These experiments are a valuable resource and are used for a wide variety 
    of scientific observations. Soil and crop samples from the experiments are 
    added to the <a href="TheRothamstedArchive.html">Rothamsted 
    archive</a> every year. </p>
  <p><a name="ListOfExperiments"> We call these old experiments the 'Classicals' 
    and they are: </a></p>
	<blockquote>
  <img src="/Graphics/SmallDot.gif" alt="Link dot"> <span><a href="#Broadbalk">Broadbalk</a> 
  - started in 1843</span> <br />
